"when the epidemic is raging, helping others is helping yourself, " a volunteer told the Beijing News.

The full text is 3871 words and takes about 7 minutes to read

As at 2400 hours on 12 February, a cumulative total of 1,101 confirmed cases had been reported in Xiangyang. The area has close contact with Wuhan people and is one of the hardest hit areas in Hubei Province.

In response to the outbreak, the Communist Youth League of Xiangyang issued a recruitment order on February 2 to begin recruiting health care professional volunteers. By 3:00 pm on February 11, the Youth League Xiangyang Municipal Committee had received 666 applications. After initial screening, a total of 356 people met the eligibility criteria.

At present, the first batch of skills training, and with professional and technical qualifications of volunteers, has been in the city of 3 hospitals to work.

In addition to medical volunteers, volunteers from all walks of life are also active. During the epidemic, isolated people living at home, lonely old people, the disabled and other groups face problems such as buying medicine, buying food inconvenient.

After the outbreak, more than 10,000 volunteers in Xiangzhou District, Xiangyang, began to help these groups run errands, psychological counseling.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A volunteer driver will be five medical staff sent to Wuhan, in the Fu River Toll Station, traffic police for their photos. Photo courtesy of the respondents

━━━━━

Send the medics back to Wuhan

Fan Caojun, a 34-year-old native of Zaoyang, Xiangyang, organized a 25-person volunteer convoy on the eve of the Lunar New Year to take Xiangyang medical staff back to the city to fight the epidemic.

Xiangyang is more than 300km from Wuhan, the provincial capital, where many people work. Fan Cao Jun told the Beijing News that under the traffic blockade, at first, seven or eight local medical staff sought help and hoped to hitch a ride back to Wuhan to go to work. "One of the nurses told me that all the recent graduates from their hospital were on the front lines and that she had six years of clinical experience and had to do everything she could to get back. "

Fan Cao Jun collected information on medical staff while summoning volunteer drivers. Because of roadblocks and other reasons, drivers can not go to the village to pick up people, they and the medical staff agreed to meet at the toll station. "there was no transport [ and ] a nurse walked 13 kilometres to meet us. "

After transporting medical staff to Wuhan, volunteer drivers will also help Xiangyang hospitals bring back supplies on the way back. Fan Caojun told the Beijing news that some deliveries from hospitals in Xiangyang could only reach the warehouse in Wuhan, and the hospital could not pick up the goods there. Therefore, Fan Caojun's motorcade would go along to help them pick up the goods.

"The route goes through about 13 counties and cities, and we set up pick-up points. On the way back, we help the hospital bring back supplies, " Fan Caojun told the Beijing News, "I got up at 6 am to coordinate, went to bed at 2 or 3 am, added at least 100 people's Wechat and received more than 200 phone calls a day. "

Some of the medical staff to pay the costs, the motorcade driver on a nominal charge 50 yuan. "It was more than 600 kilometers back and forth, and at first the drivers insisted on being free. [ later ] I suggested they take the money for food and water for the day. "

Drivers also pay attention to their own protection to ensure the safety of medical staff. Drive the process as far as possible ventilation, departure, arrival, return to disinfection, each car an average of two or three times a day disinfection. Some community groups also donated masks, gloves and other protective equipment to the convoy.

Rough statistics, Fan Cao Jun's convoy has sent more than 300 medical personnel. Some drivers run for days without rest. "A lot of people ask me if I'm afraid of being a volunteer, of course I am. But if we don't do it, more people will be in danger, including ourselves, " Fan said.

"I fight in my own way. " Every day, Fan Cao Jun posts his work diary in his friends' circle. For example, how many applications were received, how many vehicles were sent out, how much supplies were coordinated for areas such as Xiangyang.

Bo Ruonan in protective clothing. Photo provided by interviewees

Medical volunteers to fight

In order to alleviate the shortage of medical staff in Xiangyang, on February 2, the Municipal Committee of the League of Xiangyang issued a public announcement on the recruitment of medical volunteers. Within three days, more than 600 applications had been received.

After vetting and training, 27-year-old Bo Ruonan became the first batch of volunteers recruited to work, was divided in Xiangyang Infectious Disease Hospital support. She was an ICU nurse and is now a teacher in an educational institution.

"I work shifts with the nurses at the hospital, eight-hour shifts in the morning, middle and evening. Four hours of the time will be spent in the isolation ward wearing protective clothing, monitoring the patient's vital signs, giving him fluids, delivering meals and collecting household waste,"Bu told the Beijing News.

Bo spent the Lantern Festival in an isolation ward and is getting used to the daily workload. The airtight protective clothing is extremely sultry, like drilling into the airtight greenhouse, let a person sweat, goggles on the fog, also become drops of water constantly flow to the face. "after a shift, I was so tired that I didn't want to talk, " Bu Ruonan told the Beijing News.

There are 40 patients in the isolation ward where she works. Brockmann said that the nurse she was working with had not taken a holiday since before the Spring Festival. "The day before yesterday, after the morning shift, the nurse said her calf was so painful that she could hardly feel it. "

What impressed Brockmann was that when they brought food to a patient, they always cared whether she had eaten or not, reminding her to take precautions. Some patients will frequently ask her, NUCLEIC ACID test, CT results, when out, when can go home, she consoled, "soon, we are looking forward to your good results, because we want to go home. "

She was a nurse at Xiangyang's central hospital for five years before quitting in 2016 to become a civil servant. When she saw the ad for volunteers, she signed up right away. "I have been keeping an eye on the epidemic situation, and if I were still in the medical post, I would write the letter of invitation as soon as possible, " she told the Beijing News.

During the holiday season, mitine began volunteering and was assigned to the aviation industry hospital in Xiangyang, Xiangcheng, in the Shengfeng Road Hospital district. In the isolation ward, she wore protective clothing, and another nurse for patients to deliver meals, a time more than 70 meals, but also try to meet the patient's different dietary preferences.

In addition, she also sent boiled water for patients, disinfection, psychological counseling. Disinfection is twice a day, each ward of the ground, toilet, door handles, bedside cabinet all spray again.

After taking off the protective clothing, she also had to disinfect herself, using alcohol to disinfect the nasal cavity and ear canal. When oneself have a meal, still often leave the taste of disinfector in oral cavity.

Mitine goes to work at eight o'clock every morning and leaves at two o'clock in the afternoon. Early in the morning, in order to go to the toilet, she can only try to drink less water, after work to do disinfection work, often after 4:00 p.m. "sometimes I am too tired to get out of bed, but I am responsible for the patients and myself. I must take a bath and sterilize strictly, " she told the Beijing News.

Sometimes, she would be afraid of a patient with a cough. In order not to put pressure on the patient, she could not show it, but had to be as sure as possible, "it was a once-in-a-lifetime experience. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Mi Ting is sprayed with disinfectant. Photo provided by interviewee

Running errands in the neighborhood

Xiangyang Railway Siyuan community under the jurisdiction of 10 communities. Ten female volunteers, formed the "iron four courtyard community women militia prevention and control team. ". They wear military uniforms and bear the logo of the Hubei militia on their arms. "They are like soldiers, fighting on the front line, " Huang, the community secretary for the Railway Siyuan, told the Beijing News.

Zhou Juanjuan, a 42-year-old member of the "militia prevention and control team, " is in charge of the prevention and control work in Qingheyuan community. At 5 a.m. , she began to see what the residents of the community needed. In general, residents need disinfectant, vegetables, rice and other items, and some pet owners list dog food and cat food. "If you can get it, go out and buy it. If you can't get it, send it to me, " Zhou told the Beijing News as she rode her electric bike to the supermarket at noon each day. "The supermarket owner knows me, and he knows I'm going to empty the shelves again. "

She commutes from the neighborhood to the supermarket at least three times a day, spending nearly two hours shopping. Purchase of nearly 100 catties of goods and materials classified, some hanging in the electric car handle, heavy on the back seat, she will first materials to the security room, and then inform the residents downstairs to get things.

"We used to use loudspeakers to tell people to come down and get things, and they all ran down, " she said. "We were scared. There were so many people. What about cross-infection? Then we sent separate messages. ".

There are two confirmed cases in Qingheyuan district and they are now under isolation in hospital. All residents in the unit building where the patient lives are under quarantine at home. When the residents in the building needed supplies, Zhou Juanjuan delivered them directly to their door. "Some people are afraid that if I touch too many people, I will be infected, so I will put the materials at the door, and after I leave, I will let him (them) go to get them, " said Zhou.

Shuanghuanglian was said to suppress the virus, a number of residents to help her purchase. She ran to several nearby pharmacies early in the morning, but many were sold out, and finally bought four boxes. As a result, in the afternoon, some experts refuted the rumor, and many residents abandoned it.

The elderly living alone in the community do not have a cell phone, do not know how to contact their children in isolation. Zhou Juanjuan then added their children's Wechat, every day to the elderly home, with their own mobile phone open video call, let the elderly and children chat.

Juanjuan Zhou carry alcohol, from time to time to spray a whole body. She has a disposable Hazmat suit that she wears every time she goes to the isolation unit, disinfects it, and wears it again.

In her spare time, she scours videos on her phone. "when I watch a video of a paramedic, I cry, and then I feel so strong, I have to do something, " she says

Zhang Ruican, a 22-year-old senior, is also a community volunteer. His father is an associate director of respiratory medicine at Xiangyang's First People's Hospital. On the first day of the Lunar New Year, he stood with his father in the front line of the fight against the plague.

On Feb. 6, from 8 a.m. to 4 p.m. , Zhang visited seven high-risk communities, five new pneumonia hospitals and two welfare homes to help move 700 boxes of daily protective materials. One time, the supply truck didn't arrive until 2:00 a.m. , so he went to help unload it, and he didn't get home until 4:30 a.m.

Zhang Ruican told the Beijing News that the hotline of the Xiangyang Communist Party Committee had shared some of the pressure of the 120 rescue calls, and he went to help answer the hotline to help residents complete emergency vehicle dispatch. In order to respond to calls efficiently and accurately, he catalogued and documented the problem, carefully seeking the truth.

"The situation is very serious. My father is in his 50s and sees patients every day. My job is very small, just an ordinary party member, " he told the Beijing News.

Zhou Juanjuan takes part in epidemic prevention and control work in the community. Photo courtesy of the respondents

ANTI-PNEUMONIA "heart talk hotline"

Yang Lirong is a professional psychological volunteer of the Xiangyang Social Worker's anti-pneumonia "heart talk hotline" . These days, she receives one or two dozen calls a day from the hotline.

The first call came from a 27-year-old boy, she told the Beijing News. The boy's body temperature remained at 37.2 degrees Celsius for a week. He suspected he had a new type of pneumonia, so he took the initiative to isolate and watch closely. But his parents ignored him and insisted on having dinner with him, which terrified him.

"while helping his parents, I reported his illness to the CDC and advised him to keep him isolated and under observation. I encouraged him, and you did the right thing, " Yang said.

There is also a female citizen, a colleague died of pneumonia, she called Yang Lirong, said he was very afraid, every day at home to drink, eat pepper, prevention of the virus, resulting in stomach pain, psychological pressure more. Yang Lirong on detailed inquiry, whether she had contact with colleagues, remind her more disinfection, hand washing, open the window ventilation.

"I have made up a lot of knowledge about the prevention and control of NCP, " Yang told the Beijing News. "I will spread popular science to the public, dispel rumors and pass on a stable mentality to them. ".

Before the Spring Festival, in response to the appeal of a community secretary, Yang Lirong to the community staff to do psychological counseling. She saw staff walking around the streets during the epidemic, some without masks, some eight months pregnant, Yang Lirong asked these people to withdraw, to use radio.

She found a doctor friend and raised disinfectant, gloves and masks for the community workers. "Some of them said they were not afraid to get sick, but they were afraid to infect their families. I told them that to protect ourselves is to protect our families. It is the responsibility of each of us to protect ourselves and protect our families. "

HSINKING newspaper reporter, Wang Yuqian, intern, Sun Chao editor, Zhao Kaidi proofread, Li Lijun
